COPY public.documents (document_id, title, abstract, academic_program, authors, key_features) FROM stdin;
1	WEB APPLICATION FOR CHURCH MANAGEMENT SYSTEM	Churches play an important role in the spiritual and social lives of communities. However, many religious institutions, like Jaro Cathedral in Iloilo City, continue to manage their activities using manual processes. This often leads to errors, scheduling conflicts, and poor communication among parishioners, priests, and altar servers. The main problem addressed in this study is the inefficiency of manual church management, which affects event coordination, priest assignments, altar server attendance, and appointment scheduling. To solve this, the researchers developed a Web Application for a Church Management System designed to help church administrators manage mass schedules, appointments, priest assignments, and altar server attendance using a centralized platform. Parishioners can also set appointments, track events, and receive notifications through the system. The application was developed using the Agile methodology and evaluated based on the ISO 25010 software quality standards in terms of functionality, performance, compatibility, usability, reliability, security, maintainability, portability, and safety. The results showed that the Web Application for Church Management System received an overall mean score of 4.48 with a standard deviation of 0.16, earning a "Very Satisfactory" rating. The Web Application for Church Management System proved to be a helpful tool in organizing church activities, promoting better coordination, and enhancing service delivery within the church community.	BSIT	Melbourne M. Acosta, Francine C. Camiña, Izzy C. Casiple, Mark Wryzel C. Macarobo	["Mass schedule management","Appointment scheduling","Priest assignment management","Altar server attendance tracking","Event tracking","Notification system"]
2	URBANNAV: DEVELOPMENT OF URBAN COMMUTING SYSTEM WITH INTELLIGENCE ROUTE MAPPING AND DYNAMIC FARE ESTIMATION	Iloilo City, as a rapidly growing urban center, experiences a high volume of daily commuters and tourists, relying heavily on Public Utility Jeepneys (PUJs) for transportation. However, commuters often face difficulties identifying the most efficient PUJ routes and estimating fares, leading to longer travel times and higher costs, particularly for unfamiliar tourists. To address these issues, this study developed UrbanNav: Development of Urban Commuting System with Intelligent Route Mapping and Dynamic Fare Estimation, a mobile application that integrates GPS and Dijkstra’s algorithm to compute the shortest PUJ routes and provide real-time navigation, fare estimation based on LTFRB standards, and traffic-aware alternatives using Google Maps. Developed using the Agile Software Development Model, UrbanNav followed an iterative process of planning, development, testing, and feedback integration. The system was evaluated based on ISO 25010 software quality standards. Overall, UrbanNav earned an average rating of 4.5 (Excellent), signifying its effectiveness and potential impact on Iloilo City’s transportation sector. In conclusion, UrbanNav is a functional, secure, and highly usable mobile solution for urban commuters. It effectively resolves long-standing navigation and fare estimation challenges and shows strong promise for future enhancements in scalability, adaptability, and system maintenance.	BSIT	Diana Marie M. Aguas, Carl Frederick C. Delicana, Mamerto F. Gonzales Jr., LG Grace C. Sabio	["GPS integration","Dijkstra’s algorithm routing","Real-time navigation","Dynamic fare estimation","Traffic-aware route alternatives","Google Maps integration"]
3	EPRINTS: DEVELOPMENT OF WEB-BASED SYSTEM FOR PRINTING SERVICES CUSTOMIZATION	Manual processing remains a significant challenge between customer and printing shop owner, where traditional printing shops require customers to visit physical locations to access services, which may cause limitations in customization options that are restricted to in-shop offerings. Additionally, the process can be time-consuming due to manual file submission, payments, and miscommunication. Addressing this gap, this study aimed to design and implement a comprehensive web-based system for printing services customization that allows customers to upload print-ready files, customize their orders, choose pickup or delivery, track progress, and make secure payments, while providing shop owners with tools to manage accounts, pricing, requests, job tracking, and generate transaction reports. The project sought to improve both the customer experience and operational efficiency for printing businesses. The system was built using PHP and JavaScript programming languages and followed the Iterative Waterfall Model. The system was evaluated using ISO 25010 standards, and the results showed "Very Satisfactory" with an average score of "4.6," as rated by two printing shop owners, 10 users, and 3 IT experts, meeting efficiency, response time, processing speed, compatibility, and throughput standards. The findings confirm that the system is efficient, functional, and user-friendly as an online platform. Its potential as a solution for manual processes of both customers and printing shop owners has proven successful, significantly reducing the burden and improving productivity.	BSIT	Kirby Clarence C. Alegoria, Niel Andrew C. Callanga, Mike Anthony G. Taltal, Kylene O. Joy Yanguas	["Print-ready file upload","Order customization","Pickup or delivery selection","Order progress tracking","Secure payment processing","Account management tools","Pricing management","Job tracking","Transaction report generation"]
4	Central Repository of Bureau Rating System	The Central Repository of Bureau Rating System was developed to help the\r\nschool’s designated persons in charge of every program to gather and send data online. Its\r\nmain function was to manage users, manage programs, indicators and targets, generate\r\nreports, upload supporting document(s), notify via system and SMS notification, and\r\ncompute rank. The system can also store data into the database and update it\r\nautomatically.\r\nThe administrator has full access to the system while the program directors and\r\nexternal campus directors or the users have their limitations/restrictions wherein, they can\r\nonly add, view, edit, and delete data in the system that they are authorized. The users can\r\ninput necessary data for their designated bureau/program that were then computed in the\r\nsystem.	BSIT	Almonares, Lani A., Carum, Marlyn Mae C., Esmaya, Marlon M., Petipit, Jester Jen C., Salabsab, Johnroad Q.	["User management","Program management","Indicator and target management","Report generation","Supporting document upload","System and SMS notification","Rank computation","Automated data update"]
19	MEDITRACK: ENHANCING MEDICINE AVAILABILITY THROUGH CLINIC OPTIMIZATION	This study aimed to develop and implement a MediTrack: Enhancing Medicine Availability Through Clinic Optimization system to enhance medicine availability and streamline inventory management. The system allows the doctor and medical staff to record newly delivered stocks, stocks on hand and released stocks. They can access and monitor that essential medications are accessible, improving patient care and operational efficiency.\r\nAdditionally, it generated report on the Annual Procurement Plan and Project Procurement Management Plan (APP/PPMP) based on the recorded stock that helped ensure efficient budgeting, transparency, and compliance with procurement regulations.	BSIT	Rodolfo C. Cabuctolan, Rod Stephen A. Defensor, Lucille Rose B. Geriane, Vynz Androu P. Mendiola, Ana May D. Roquero, Maegan A. Saladar	["Stock recording module","Inventory monitoring dashboard","Annual Procurement Plan report generation","Project Procurement Management Plan report generation"]
5	Faculty Evaluation System with Sentiment Analysis for Iloilo Science and Technology University	Providing quality education is a primary goal of universities, aiming to develop well-rounded individuals through engaged students and passionate faculty. This capstone project created a Faculty Evaluation System with Sentiment Analysis for Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISATU) to improve teaching quality and decision-making by addressing inefficiencies in manual and Google Forms-based evaluations. Built using PHP, MySQL, and the Gmail API, the system used the VADER model to analyze English feedback, categorizing it as positive, negative, neutral, or other, and presented numerical data through charts. Its goals are to enhance data collection, track participation, and produce actionable reports. Pilot-tested with 30 students, 1 supervisor, 4 research staff, and 5 IT experts, the system was assessed using the UTAUT framework, earning excellent ratings: Performance Expectancy (4.786875), Effort Expectancy (4.605), Social Influence (4.45), and Facilitating Conditions (4.569375), with an overall evaluation result of 4.603, rated as Excellent, indicating strong user acceptance due to its utility, ease of use, and institutional support. The system successfully supported comprehensive evaluations, real-time monitoring, automated notifications, and standardized Excel reports, though slight variations suggest enhancing peer influence and technical support. Recommendations include improving user management, adding SMS notifications, and creating a tailored sentiment analysis library for academic contexts to maintain effectiveness and support educational quality at ISATU.	BSIT	John Kenneth G. Ambag, Jan Vince L. Mendoza, Leo Angelo N. Sorianosos, Franches John K. Gilbaliga	["VADER sentiment analysis","Gmail API integration","Numerical data visualization","Real-time monitoring","Automated notifications","Standardized Excel reports","Data collection tracking"]
6	Furniture Management System	The Furniture Management System aimed to improve the operational efficiency of\r\nthe Integrated Income and Resources Generation Program (IIRGP) Office of Iloilo Science\r\nand Technology University by enhancing existing manual processes through a more\r\nstreamlined, web-based approach. The system serves as a tool to assist users in managing\r\nfurniture products, customizing product details, and overseeing transactions from order\r\nplacement to fulfillment. It includes features for generating job contracts and job requests,\r\ncreating QR codes for order release and acceptance, and generating income statement\r\nreport for financial tracking. Customers are able to view products, submit customization\r\nrequests, and receive notifications regarding their orders.\r\nThe researchers utilized the Prototyping Model as the software development\r\nmethodology. This approach involved creating an initial prototype based on the system’s\r\ndesign, which was tested and refined through multiple cycles of user feedback. The\r\ndevelopment process followed four main phases: planning, analysis, design, and\r\nimplementation. User feedback was continuously incorporated to improve the system,\r\nresulting in a final version that closely aligned with user needs and expectations.\r\nThe system's functionality, reliability, usability, performance efficiency, security,\r\ncompatibility, maintainability, and portability were evaluated based on ISO 25010 software\r\nquality standards, resulting in an overall rating of "Very Good." This rating indicates that\r\nthe system is effective and efficient in managing furniture operations and is reliable for\r\nfuture use.	BSIT	John Michael Amor, Darlien Riey S. Escleto, Ansel Ann A. Janas, Jesa Pearl L. Mallorca, Jorin J. Panisa, Nathan Scott M. Pama, Jeanro P. Tapalla	["Job contract generation","Job request creation","QR code generation","Order release tracking","Order acceptance tracking","Income statement report","Product customization","Customer order notifications"]
7	SMART WATER REFILLING SYSTEM	The Smart Water Refilling System aimed to allow registration of water refilling\r\nstation, manage user accounts, monitor water level of water tank, manage inventory,\r\nmanage customer order and schedule, Evaluate the System based on ISO 25010 (in terms\r\nof Functional Suitability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility, Interaction Capability,\r\nReliability, Security, Maintainability, Flexibility and Safety).\r\nThe system enables the administrator to manage the registration of the water\r\nrefilling stations. The owner, when logging into the system, can monitor water level,\r\nmanage orders, inventory, products and its employee account that they can use to log in a\r\niv\r\nmobile application. The employee can use the mobile application to manage the customer’s\r\norder and set the schedule for delivery and update the status of their order. Then, the\r\ncustomers can select their preferred water station and have a pre order of the products.\r\nThey can add, edit, cancel, and view their order status.\r\nThe Smart Water Refilling System was evaluated using white box testing and black\r\nbox testing by IT experts based on the International Organization of Standardization (ISO\r\n25010). The overall evaluation of the Smart Water Refilling System, based on the ISO\r\n25010 software quality standards, received a rating of (M=4.59, SD=0.04) and was\r\nclassified as 5Excellent.6 This indicates that the system effectively delivers functional\r\noutputs aligned with its intended purpose. ISO 25010 standard was used in the evaluation\r\nof the software in terms of Functional Suitability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility,\r\nInteraction Capability, Reliability, Security, Maintainability, Flexibility and Safety.	BSIT	Daneza Khay A. Ariente, Jad Prixie G. Buque, Jeodalyn R. Edulag, Carl Angelo U. Eisma, Carl Emmanuel C. Pacardo, Sherwin F. Vales	["Water refilling station registration","User account management","Water level monitoring","Inventory management","Customer order management","Delivery scheduling","Mobile application order updates"]
8	THE CONNECTED CYCLE: BIKE RENTAL WITH SMART SECURITY AND MONITORING SYSTEM	The increasing urban traffic congestion, environmental concerns, and rising\r\ndemand for sustainable transportation have driven the need for innovative mobility\r\nsolutions. This study aims to design and develop a bike rental with smart security and\r\nmonitoring system designed to offer a user-friendly mode of urban transport. The system\r\nfeatures a mobile friendly web-based application integrated with physical smart locking\r\nmechanisms to facilitate operational efficiency and security measures for the rented bikes.\r\nAlso, it can locate docking stations and include QR code-based scanning to rent a bike.\r\nOnline payment was integrated and a GPS tracking for real-time monitoring. The system\r\nwas evaluated using the Unified Theory of Acceptance and Use of Technology (UTAUT)\r\nfocusing on performance expectancy, effort expectancy, social influence, facilitating\r\nconditions, and behavioural intention with an overall mean of 4.56. Findings revealed a\r\nhigh user satisfaction and acceptance demonstrating the system’s viability for broader\r\nadoption in urban areas, supporting initiatives in green mobility and smart city\r\ndevelopment.	BSIT	Amador Adrian C. Azarraga, Karl Rylan A. Bacugan, Yuri T. Dignadice, Earl Jesri D. Siva, Vanz Dezter G. Sumande	["Mobile friendly web application","Physical smart locking mechanisms","Docking station locator","QR code-based bike rental","Online payment integration","GPS real-time tracking"]
9	Puluy-an: A Mobile Application for Lipat Bahay Services in Iloilo City	This study focuses on developing a mobile application, Puluy-an, to improve "Lipat Bahay" services in Iloilo City. As urbanization grows and the demand for moving services increases, the traditional methods of booking and communication have become inefficient and time-consuming. This research aims to create an online platform that allows customers to easily book moving services, communicate with service providers, and make secure payments.\r\nThe application will feature a user-friendly interface, multiple payment options, and integrated customer support to streamline the booking process. Additionally, it will include a ratings and reviews system to promote service quality and accountability.\r\nService providers will benefit from tools that allow them to manage bookings more efficiently, ultimately improving operational workflows and customer satisfaction.\r\nTo ensure the application's quality, the research will evaluate the platform based on international software standards, with emphasis on usability, reliability, and security. In the long term, this study aims to lay the groundwork for future enhancements, such as the integration of additional services and the continuous improvement of user experience based on client feedback	BSIT	Jed Simplicio E. Bacabac Jr., Kevin S. Jancilan, Nikko P. Lozada, Joselito T. Laporga, Rizza Mae C. Maduque, John Francis M. Villagracia	["User-friendly interface","Multiple payment options","Integrated customer support","Ratings and reviews system","Booking management tools"]
10	Library Management System	The Library Management System (LMS) was developed to address inefficiencies in the traditional, manual operations of the Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U) library, where attendance and book tracking were prone to delays, inaccuracies, and human error. Recognizing the need to modernize these processes, this study aimed to design and develop a web-based LMS that integrates QR code technology to streamline attendance monitoring, manage borrowing and returning transactions, and generate data-driven reports to support decision-making for future book acquisitions. The system was developed using a throwaway prototyping model, ensuring continuous feedback from users including librarians, faculty, and students throughout the design, implementation, and testing phases. Key functionalities include real-time QR-based attendance tracking, categorization of library materials, book reservation and status updates, damage reporting, and the generation of statistical and operational reports. The system’s performance was rigorously evaluated following the ISO 25010 software quality model, focusing on functional suitability, usability, performance efficiency, reliability, security, maintainability, and portability. The results showed the LMS achieved a “Very Good” overall rating (M=4.12), performing particularly in functional completeness, efficiency, and usability, while noting areas for improvement in portability. These outcomes highlight the system’s capacity to enhance library operations, reduce manual workload, and improve user satisfaction. Thus, this study provides valuable implications for academic libraries seeking to integrate modern technologies, demonstrating how digital systems can strengthen library management, support strategic resource planning, and elevate the overall user experience.	BSIT	Carlo D. Balano, Dave Mclin T. Bene, Patrick A. Pirote, John Windrick Sucias, Von John S. Suropia	["QR-based attendance tracking","Library materials categorization","Book reservation system","Book status updates","Damage reporting","Statistical report generation","Operational report generation"]
11	ISATour: A MOBILE-BASED VIRTUAL GAME THROUGH INNOVATION AND DISCOVERY	The study developed ISATour: A Mobile-based Virtual Game Through Innovation and Discovery, a gamified virtual campus tour application designed for Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U) – La Paz Campus. This project addresses challenges encountered in traditional campus tours such as limited accessibility, time constraints, and lack of engagement by offering an interactive mobile game that allows users to navigate a 2D side-scrolling representation of the university.\r\nThe system enables users to explore buildings and facilities, interact with digital objects, and participate in quizzes to enhance learning and immersion. It was developed using the Godot Engine for the Android Game and follows a prototype development model. System features include admin and player account management, quiz generation, and a scoring system, with content based on actual information and visuals collected from ISAT U.	BSIT	Haissem E. Batilo, Eunica A. Cayao, Izabelle O. Deloviar, Jerneal A. Jermia, Kent John D. Naral, Johnson L. Tangista, Rebrinjoroy N. Teologo	["2D side-scrolling navigation","Admin account management","Player account management","Quiz generation","Scoring system","Digital object interaction"]
12	CULINARY CONVERGENCE: INGREDIENT-BASED MENU PLANNING	This study presents the development of Culinary Convergence: Ingredient-Based\r\nMenu Planning, a system designed to simplify meal planning for chefs, carinderia owners,\r\nand individuals. The system integrates user preferences, available ingredients, and cost\r\nconsiderations to generate customized menus. By ingredient-based planning, the platform\r\neffectively addresses issues like limited ingredient availability, lack of inspiration, and food\r\nwaste.\r\nThe system features a user-friendly interface that allows users to input ingredients,\r\ncustomize meal plans, and generate multiple dish options. Additionally, chefs can showcase\r\ntheir skills by uploading portfolios and applying for chef roles, encouraging culinary\r\ncreativity. The platform also includes subscription-based access to premium recipes and a\r\ncommission system to support chef earnings.	BSIT	Princess Benliro, Keena June G. Cabucos, Quinnie P. De Asis, Josh Nil O. Java, Edward Vince J. Sazon	["Ingredient input interface","Customized meal plan generation","Multiple dish option generation","Chef portfolio uploads","Chef role application","Subscription-based premium recipes","Commission system for chefs"]
13	Web-based Evaluation System	This study aimed to develop an Web-based Evaluation System. The system was\r\ndeveloped at Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U) main campus, La Paz,\r\nIloilo City. The researcher employed the Throw-away Prototyping Model method in\r\ndesigning the system. The researcher had undergone the different phases of Throw-away\r\nPrototyping Model such as Planning, Analysis, Design and Implementation.\r\nThe system was designed and developed as web applications that enable the\r\nguidance counsellor to manage the account of the students. The guidance counsellor can\r\nalso manage the exam schedule, exam, and results of the student. The system systematized\r\n5\r\nthe interpretation result based on the weight value of each choice chosen by the student\r\nalso the system manage the department which students belong.\r\nAfter the development, the system was evaluated using International\r\nOrganization for Standardization (ISO) 25010 product quality model in terms of functional\r\nsuitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, usability, reliability, security,\r\nmaintainability and portability. The evaluators were Computer Instructor who are also\r\nfreelance programmer and web developers from different colleges and universities and\r\nexperts. The evaluation data were analysed using mean.	BSIT	Garret Vence S. Bereber, Joshua F. Jamili, Winter H. Mogatar, Ray Matthew M. De La Cruz, Kenneth Adrian M. Tono	["Student account management","Exam schedule management","Exam result management","Interpretation result systematization","Department management"]
14	PAY ‘N PRINT: A SELF-SERVICE PRINTING SYSTEM	In academic institutions, printing remains a vital service for both students and\r\nfaculty members. However, traditional printing setups often encounter inefficiencies such\r\nas long queues, limited access, and manual payment processes. To address these challenges,\r\nthis study developed a self-service printing system, a kiosk-based solution aimed at\r\nstreamlining document printing through automation and digital integration. The system\r\nallows users to scan a QR code for instant access, upload documents in Word or PDF\r\nformat, preview content, and customize print settings including page selection, layout, and\r\ncolor mode. Optical Character Recognition (OCR) is used to analyze documents and\r\nautomatically estimate printing costs, thereby promoting transparency and operational\r\nefficiency. Payments are processed through a secure, cashless platform using PayPal. The\r\nsystem was developed using the agile methodology, which involves iterative sprints\r\ncovering concept brainstorming, system design, development, quality assurance and\r\ndeployment. A purposive sampling technique was employed to select (n=20) respondents,\r\nconsisting of IT students and professionals. System evaluation was conducted using the\r\nISO 25010 Software Quality Standards, which assess eight quality characteristics:\r\nfunctional suitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, usability, reliability, security,\r\nmaintainability, and portability. Respondents evaluated the system using a 5-point Likert\r\nscale, where 5 indicated Excellent and 1 indicated Poor. The system achieved an overall\r\nmean score (M=4.24), classified as Excellent. Among the criteria, compatibility obtained\r\nthe highest mean (M = 4.65), reflecting the intuitive design and ease of use of the system.\r\nIn contrast, security received the lowest mean score (M=3.23), indicating a Satisfactory\r\nrating and suggesting areas for future improvement. Thus, the Pay ‘n Print system provides\r\na modern, efficient, and user- centered solution for self-service printing in academic\r\nenvironment	BSIT	Nikko Bryan F. Bernardo, Ann Erika D. Gabales, Jisielle Mae P. Lago, Junmar S. Mahipus, Cindy L. Urdas	["QR code scanning","Document upload","Print preview","Print settings customization","Optical Character Recognition","Automatic cost estimation","Cashless payment integration","Kiosk-based interface"]
15	FishCatchLandingMonitoringSystem	Fishing remains a crucial source of livelihood and food security in the Philippines; however, the Department of Agriculture’s (DA) continued reliance on manual paper-based systems has resulted in inefficiencies, data inaccuracies, and limited access to real-time information. These limitations hinder timely decision-making and effective fishery management. Thus, this study aimed to develop a fish-catch monitoring system that records a fisherman’s daily catch. This system allows fish enumerators to digitally input essential information, including species, size, weight, and landing locations, via mobile devices. Key features include real-time data validation, centralized cloud storage, and automated report generation with outputs categorized by species and geographic distribution. The evaluation was based on the ISO/IEC 25010 software quality model and focused on functionality, usability, reliability, and efficiency. Results reveal an overall mean score of 4.1, described as “Very Good,” demonstrating the system has significantly improved data accuracy, accessibility, and transparency. In addition, the digital transformation of the fish catch landing and monitoring system enhances operational efficiency and ensures timely access to data. By providing accurate and visualized data, DA and other stakeholders can make informed decisions and respond proactively to changes in fish stocks and market demand.	BSIT	KenieRoseB. Bolivar, DanKesterC.Campoid, Jafet M. Dejulian, LadyEarlAnneD.Laganipa, Kris Ann S. Tabiano, SybelMarieM.Villarma	["Real-time data validation","Centralized cloud storage","Automated report generation","Mobile data input","Species categorization","Geographic distribution outputs"]
16	THE DEVELOPMENT OF “PRODUCTLOCA”: A PRODUCT FINDER SYSTEM	The development of “ProductLoca”: A Product Finder System resulted in a portal-type system designed to allocate and manage products, business information, store details, floor plans, kiosk device locations, and generate a list of frequently searched products. This study aims to address the inefficient and time-consuming process that customers face when locating products. The system, developed using PHP and MySQL, enables super administrators and administrators to manage and analyze product search data, configure store information, and potentially oversee user accounts. It also enables customers to quickly and easily locate products within the store through a search functionality, access detailed product information, and utilize store mapping features for efficient navigation. The system was evaluated based on ISO 25010 standards, including functionality, reliability, usability, efficiency, security, compatibility, maintainability, and portability. The researchers used purposive sampling to recruit respondents, including twenty (20) shoppers, ten (10) students, ten (10) mall employees, and four (4) information and communication technology (ICT) experts who were also store managers. These ICT experts, comprising development specialists, IT professionals, and professors, evaluated the system using the eight ISO quality standards. The evaluation results indicated that “ProductLoca”: A Product Finder System met the study’s objectives and performed effectively, achieving an overall rating of 4.35 (Very Satisfactory). Functional Suitability was rated 4.43 (Very Satisfactory), Performance Efficiency 4.41 (Very Satisfactory), Compatibility 4.37 (Very Satisfactory), Usability 4.49 (Very Satisfactory), Reliability 4.37 (Very Satisfactory), Maintainability 4.15 (Satisfactory), and Portability 4.32 (Very Satisfactory).	BSIT	Elizabeth Ann C. Bravo, Mark Ian C. Selguera, Isaac Asreil D. Sermona, Noevie Jane C. Sumido	["Product search functionality","Store mapping features","Product and business information management","Floor plan management","Kiosk device location tracking","Frequently searched products list","Product search data analysis","User account management"]
17	SMART TRANSIT: REAL-TIME MODERNIZED JEEPNEY TRACKING FOR PASSENGERS	A reliable transportation system is essential for reducing traffic congestion, which is a common problem in Iloilo City. By offering efficient public transport, which helps ease road traffic and makes daily commuting more convenient. With the use of advanced technologies like GPS tracking [1], modernized jeepneys have become easier to monitor in real time. This is especially helpful for students and daily commuters who often experience long waits and uncertainty about bus arrivals.\r\nDespite the improvements, many commuters still face delays, causing stress and inconvenience. To help solve this problem, this study developed a system called Smart Transit: Real-Time Modernized Jeepney Tracking for Passengers. The system includes real-time jeepney tracking and a location-pinning feature that lets passengers mark where they want to be picked up. This helps conductors and operators respond more efficiently. The project was carried out at Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U) Iloilo City Campus and followed the Agile Software Development Model. The system was tested and evaluated using the ISO 25010 standard for software quality and participants were chosen through purposive sampling. The results showed that the system met its goals and performed excellently in terms of functionality, ease of use and overall effectiveness.	BSIT	JAY M. BUENCUCHILLO, CHERRY MAE T. CASTILLON, JENDY T. CASTILON, JOVY ROSE D. DELACRUZ, LORENZ DANIEL S. FUASAN, FANILYN T. GAMARCHA	["Real-time jeepney tracking","Location-pinning feature","GPS Tracking"]
18	Private Community Security System: Car Visitor Tracking using GIS and GPS	Private subdivisions and gated communities commonly rely on traditional security measures such as manual logbooks, CCTV surveillance, and gate personnel to monitor incoming vehicles. While these tools provide basic monitoring, they are prone to human error, data inconsistency, and a lack of real-time response, making it difficult to efficiently verify and manage visitor access. These limitations can lead to gaps in security, increased workload for personnel, and delayed responses during peak hours or emergencies. There is a growing need for integrated, automated security systems that improve accuracy, accountability, and real-time monitoring. This study developed the Private Community Security System: Car Visitor Tracking using GIS and GPS, an innovative solution that integrates Geographic Information System (GIS) mapping, Global Positioning System (GPS) tracking, and biometric fingerprint verification. The system uses a fingerprint-secured GPS tracker attached to each visitor’s vehicle, which transmits live location data to a web-based dashboard. This allows security personnel to monitor visitor vehicles in real-time while ensuring the integrity and identity of each visitor through biometric verification. Additionally, the system records historical movement data for auditing and incident analysis. To evaluate the system’s performance, the study employed the ISO 25010 software quality model, gathering feedback from 19 participants, including IT professionals, security guards, and general users. Key metrics included functional suitability, usability, performance efficiency, maintainability, and portability. The results indicated an overall Excellent rating, validating the system's effectiveness in improving visitor management. Minor areas for improvement included compatibility and reliability, which did not significantly impact the system’s performance. This research demonstrates that integrating tracking, authentication, and real-time monitoring provides a robust, scalable solution to modernize security operations in gated communities. The system offers enhanced visibility, faster response times, and improved control over vehicle entry, making it a valuable tool for private community safety.	BSIT	Nash Julian A. Cabalfin, Jeremiah C. Sim, Krystal Rose M. Rizardo, Mechelle T. Simpron	["GIS mapping integration","GPS vehicle tracking","Biometric fingerprint verification","Fingerprint-secured GPS tracker","Real-time location transmission","Web-based monitoring dashboard","Historical movement data recording"]
20	U-Sync: Unifying Event System	In educational institutions and multi-department organizations, managing events effectively is a recurring challenge due to fragmented communication channels and inconsistent scheduling practices. Events are often announced separately through various departmental social media platforms, resulting in redundancy, missed opportunities, and poor coordination. To address this issue, U-Sync: Unifying Events System was developed as a comprehensive web and mobile application that centralizes event management. The system introduces a structured, role-based framework with distinct user roles Administrators, Managers, and Viewers designed to streamline event coordination, enhance user engagement, and foster community collaboration. Key features include dynamic calendar generation, role and permission management, email push notifications, OTP-based authentication for secure access, and subscription-enabled administrative tools. U-Sync’s performance was evaluated using the ISO 25010 software quality standards, which assess nine critical dimensions: Functional Suitability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility, Usability, Reliability, Security, Maintainability, Flexibility, and Safety. Results indicated an overall “Excellent” rating, with Safety achieving the highest score, while Reliability was identified as an area for further improvement. In conclusion, U-Sync demonstrates significant potential in improving information dissemination and event management within institutional settings. It lays a strong foundation for unified communication and efficient planning. Future enhancements are recommended to focus on increasing system dependability, scalability, user engagement, and expanding the scope of real-time notification features.	BSIT	Carlo J’naed Lyton A. Cahuya, Joseph Bennett P. Dairo, Elmar Augustine S. Fernandez, Gabriel R. Leornas, Quennie R. Tabladillo	["Dynamic calendar generation","Role and permission management","Email push notifications","OTP-based authentication","Subscription-enabled administrative tools"]
21	VIRTUEBANWA: A GAMIFIED INSTRUCTIONAL MATERIAL FOR GMRC	The traditional education system faces persistent challenges such as limited\r\npersonalization, rigid curricula, and insufficient student engagement, particularly in values\r\neducation. In response, this study introduces VirtueBanwa, a gamified instructional\r\nmaterial designed to enhance the teaching and learning experience of Good Manners and\r\nRight Conduct (GMRC) among Grade 1 students in Iloilo. Anchored on the Department of\r\nEducation’s MATATAG Curriculum and Republic Act No. 11476, which mandates\r\nGMRC as a core subject, the project leverages gamification to deliver moral and ethical\r\nlessons in an interactive, student-centered manner. Using a system prototyping\r\nmethodology, the 2D mobile game was developed with Unity and C#, integrating\r\nsimulations, visual and audio elements, and core gameplay mechanics aligned with the\r\nMost Essential Learning Competencies (MELCs) of GMRC. The system includes features\r\nfor managing student and classroom data, delivering lessons through play, and tracking\r\nand updating student progress. Its effectiveness was evaluated using ISO 25010 standards\r\nthrough purposive sampling of five teachers, and five IT practitioners from a rural school\r\nin Iloilo. Results indicate an overall "Excellent" rating (4.26 on the Likert Scale),\r\ndemonstrating the system’s success in fostering engagement, improving retention of moral\r\nvalues, and supporting the holistic development of learners through innovative educational\r\ntechnology.	BSIT	Wylby Von M. Cainglet, Shian Carlo C. Celebrado, Rojann Francis A. Del Carmen, Angel Janica Marie T. De Jesus, Mark Lexter T. Sicabalo	["2D mobile game development","Simulations integration","Visual and audio elements","Core gameplay mechanics","Student data management","Classroom data management","Lesson delivery through play","Student progress tracking"]
22	CROWDRELIEF: EMPOWERING DISASTER RELIEF THROUGH CROWDFUNDING INNOVATION	CrowdRelief is a web-based crowdfunding platform designed to improve disaster relief by tackling inefficiencies in resource distribution, stakeholder coordination, and donation transparency. It aims to streamline relief efforts, promoting better coordination, resource use, and trust in donation processes. The platform facilitates the launch, management, and donation of disaster relief campaigns, catering primarily to donors and fundraisers through various donation types including monetary and in-kind contributions. The platform’s development followed an iterative prototyping methodology. Interviews were conducted to gather requirements from non-governmental organizations, local government units, and individual donors. The platform was built using PHP and MySQL, incorporating secure user authentication, real-time donation tracking, and an intuitive interface for stakeholder interaction. Alpha and beta testing phases, incorporating stakeholder feedback, enabled iterative refinements to ensure the platform’s usability and alignment with disaster relief operational requirements. The software's quality was evaluated by a panel comprising three (3) IT experts, one (1) NGO representative, two (2) LGU representatives, and fifty (50) random donors, utilizing the ISO/IEC 25010 standard. The assessment yielded an overall "Very Satisfactory" rating, with specific scores as follows: Functional Suitability (4.39), Performance Efficiency (4.11), Compatibility (4.29), Usability (4.28), Reliability (4.25), Security (4.25), Maintainability (4.23), and Portability (4.26). These findings substantiate the platform's efficacy, stability, and suitability for operational deployment. CrowdRelief provides a scalable solution that addresses transparency and coordination gaps in existing disaster relief systems, offering potential for broader crisis response applications and advancing disaster management practices.	BSIT	Hanna Jane C. Calanuga, Carl A. Catoto, Anne Monique D. Palmaira, Jessie Rey A. Prandas	["Secure user authentication","Real-time donation tracking","Donation campaign management","Monetary and in-kind contributions","Stakeholder interaction interface"]
23	Solis Tabula Vestigator: An Automated Solar Tracking and Monitoring System	In recent years, the global transition toward sustainable energy has emphasized the\r\nneed for innovative solutions to maximize the efficiency of renewable resources,\r\nparticularly solar power. Solar energy is abundant and clean, but its efficiency largely\r\ndepends on how effectively a solar panel can capture sunlight. Traditional fixed-position\r\npanels are limited by their static orientation, leading to suboptimal energy collection as the\r\nsun moves across the sky, resulting in reduced energy efficiency. To address this, the study\r\ndeveloped the Solis Tabula Vestigator, an automated solar tracking and monitoring system\r\ndesigned to optimize energy collection through dynamic panel adjustment and real-time\r\nperformance tracking. The system features a solar tracking device capable of both rotation\r\nand tilting, allowing it to align with the sun more effectively throughout the day. A custom-\r\nbuilt web application complements the device by enabling users to remotely monitor sensor\r\ndata, compare energy performance between automated and static systems on both daily and\r\nhourly bases, and export data as CSV reports for further analysis. Results from daily and\r\nhourly comparisons show that the automated system consistently harvested more energy\r\nthan the static panel. The user interface provided intuitive visualizations and access to\r\nenergy reports and sensor readings, and data exports for in-depth analysis. To ensure\r\nquality, the system was evaluated using the ISO/IEC 25010 framework, which assessed\r\nnine software quality characteristics: functional suitability, performance efficiency,\r\ncompatibility, interaction capability, reliability, security, maintainability, flexibility, and\r\nsafety. The system received an overall excellent rating of 4.13. In conclusion, the Solis\r\nTabula Vestigator successfully achieved its development objectives and proved to be an\r\nefficient, reliable, and user-friendly solution for enhancing solar energy utilization through\r\nautomated tracking and real-time performance monitoring.	BSIT	Capanang, Grace Anne E., Cartoja, Jhona Mae C., Pajarillo, Daisy Ann O., Tahumar, Jan James Lennox L.	["Solar panel rotation","Solar panel tilting","Real-time performance tracking","Remote sensor data monitoring","Energy performance comparison","CSV data export","Custom web application","Dynamic panel adjustment"]
24	SOWSMART: AUTOMATED FEEDER FOR HOG RAISERS	This study aimed to develop SowSmart: Automated Feeder for Hog Raisers, a sys-\r\ntem that addresses the challenges faced by hog raisers in efficiently managing feeding\r\nschedules for their livestock. One of the common problems of hog raisers is the incon-\r\nsistency in feeding times and portioning, which affects the health and growth of their\r\nhogs. The system focuses on automating feeding schedules, tracking hog metrics, and\r\nmaintaining detailed feeding records to ensure optimal livestock management. The ap-\r\nplication enables users to oversee pig pens, monitor individual hogs, and schedule feed-\r\nings seamlessly.\r\nThe system's features also include the ability to track hog metrics, automate feeding\r\nprocesses, and improve management efficiency through its intuitive interface. SowSmart\r\nwas tested using End-to-End and White Box Testing methods. These methodologies en-\r\nsured that the system performed flawlessly both functionally and structurally. Respond-\r\nents evaluated the system using the ISO 25010 standard and rated it as 9Excellent.	BSIT	Jhan Rei C. Congreso, Chanshai Marie C. Denila, Jan Christian U. Gotuato, Ian Carl V. Jablo, Mark Timothy V. Niño, Spencer O. Tajonera, Jonji E. Tamara	["Automated feeding schedules","Hog metrics tracking","Feeding records maintenance","Pig pen oversight","Individual hog monitoring","Feeding process automation","Intuitive user interface"]
25	Customized 3D Fashion Design and Order Management System	This study aimed to develop a customized 3D fashion design and order management system that integrates effective order management with advanced 3D modeling, offering a relevant and innovative solution for the modern fashion industry. This study addresses the shortcomings of traditional fashion design processes, which are often characterized by inefficiencies, limited personalization, and a lack of real-time visualization. Using a customized 3D fashion design and order management system enables users to create customized clothing by selecting fabric types, colors, and design features through real-time 3D modeling. The system offers seamless order management functionalities, including customer chat support, order monitoring dashboards, automated billing statement generation, and real-time notification updates. The system was evaluated based on the ISO 25010 software quality model and rated on eight prominent characteristics: functional suitability, performance efficiency, compatibility, usability, reliability, security, maintainability, and portability. Evaluation findings, collated from diverse respondents such as IT professionals, business managers, employees, and students, depicted satisfactory performance in all the quality characteristics. The result revealed an overall mean score of 3.79, described as “Very Satisfactory”. The Customized 3D Fashion Design and Order Management System, successfully bridges the gap between digital fashion design and practical manufacturing processes. It offers a sustainable, efficient, and user-friendly platform that meets modern industry demands while providing customers with greater control and personalization in their fashion choices. The positive evaluation outcomes validate the system's potential for real-world application and future expansion in the digital fashion marketplace.	BSIT	John Paul V. Cordero, Estanislao S. Delariate III, Angeline I. Griño, Ghe Pee O. Mamon, Bevelyn T. Tamallana	["3D clothing customization","Fabric type selection","Color selection","Design feature selection","Real-time 3D modeling","Customer chat support","Order monitoring dashboard","Automated billing statement generation","Real-time notification updates"]
26	SERVICE CONNECT IT: REQUEST AND SUPPORT SYSTEM	The Service Connect IT: Request and Support System is a system that aims to\r\ndigitalize service requests made by the users. The MIS department, however, is still using the\r\ntraditional method of taking requests in a paper-based form, which result in the requests that\r\ngoing missing, and getting delayed.\r\nThe system provides a user with an easy and convenient way of processing their\r\nrequest which is through an automated request form that is made possible with the system\r\nnamed Service Connect IT: Request and Support System. The user, specifically the\r\nFaculty/Staff can start initiating their request through filling up the necessary items in\r\nsubmitting the request. Technical Staff will then be the one to process the requests made by\r\nthe faculty/staff until they become resolved. Finally, the MIS Staff will be responsible for\r\naccepting or declining requests, providing prioritization, managing the user’s account, and\r\ntracking the request history. The Service Connect IT: Request and Support System was tested\r\nusing white box testing by IT experts based on the International Organization of\r\nStandardization (ISO 25010). The Reliability received the highest rating based on ISO 25010\r\nquality standards with the (M=4.7, SD=0.10). This result implies that the overall Reliability\r\nof The system is “Excellent” in terms of Reliability. This concludes that the system meets the\r\nspecified conditions and covers all the specified tasks and user objectives characterized by\r\nISO 25010.	BSIT	John Adrian R. Custorio, Glen Brian G. Decado, Jimmie S. Hechanova Jr, Janpaul Jabien, Darlene Joy A. Quebral	["Automated request form","Request prioritization","User account management","Request history tracking","Technical staff request processing"]
27	ISAT U MEDICAL CLINIC MANAGEMENT SYSTEM WITH CHATBOT	The study aimed to design and develop the ISAT-U Medical Clinic Management System with Chatbot to improve the management of patient information, symptom assessment, appointment scheduling, SMS notifications, and the generation of initial diagnoses. The system was also evaluated based on the ISO/IEC 25010 software quality standards, which include functional suitability, stability, reliability, usability, performance efficiency, security, compatibility, maintainability, and portability. To assess the system’s effectiveness, the researchers used purposive and convenience sampling techniques, selecting a total of 25 respondents 21 Information Technology students and 4 IT experts who had relevant knowledge about the system.\r\nThe findings showed that the system met all its intended objectives. Specifically, Functional Stability received the highest rating of 4.29, followed by Compatibility with 4.21, Usability with 4.17, Security and Performance Efficiency both at 4.10, and Portability with 4.08. All criteria were rated as “Very Satisfactory,” indicating that the system is functional, secure, and user-friendly.\r\nAlthough the results were highly positive, the evaluation also highlighted opportunities for further enhancement, particularly in optimizing performance and improving system portability. Overall, the system has proven to be an effective, efficient, and scalable solution for modernizing healthcare services within the university.	BSIT	Angelica B. Dela Peña, Lea June C. Camino, Joje-Ann Opiane, Kristine Joy F. Ferrer, Mark Lourence O. Pahilga	["Patient information management","Symptom assessment","Appointment scheduling","SMS notifications","Initial diagnosis generation"]
28	LEAFLENS: DEVELOPMENT OF MOBILE APPLICATION USING IMAGEANALYSIS FOR OPTIMAL RICE HARVESTING AND FERTILIZATION	Rice farming remains an essential component of food security in the Philippines.\r\nDespite technological advancements, many local farmers continue to assess nitrogen levels\r\nin rice crops manually by relying on the Leaf Color Chart (LCC), a traditional tool for\r\ndetermining leaf health based on color. While widely used, this method is subjective and\r\nprone to inaccuracies, as it heavily depends on human perception and environmental\r\nconditions. The primary problem identified in this study is the inefficiency and unreliability\r\nof manual leaf color assessment, which often leads to improper fertilizer application. This\r\nmay result in either nutrient deficiency or over-fertilization, negatively affecting crop yield.\r\nTo address this issue, the researchers developed LeafLens, a mobile application designed\r\nto assist farmers in evaluating the nitrogen status of rice leaves through image analysis.\r\nThe application utilizes a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN), specifically the\r\nMobileNetV2 architecture, to classify rice leaf colors accurately and provide data-driven\r\nrecommendations regarding fertilizer application and optimal harvest timing. The findings\r\nof the study indicate that LeafLens achieved high accuracy in classifying leaf color. The\r\napplication successfully delivered appropriate fertilizer suggestions and harvest period\r\nestimates. These results demonstrate the potential of LeafLens to support precision farming\r\nand contribute to sustainable agricultural practices.	BSIT	JR G. Delgado, Bryce Kendric D. Saladar, Vince Ryan C. Taghap, John Kenneth D. Tan	["Image analysis of rice leaves","Convolutional Neural Network classification","MobileNetV2 architecture","Nitrogen status evaluation","Fertilizer application recommendations","Optimal harvest timing estimation"]
29	SKOLAR KONEK: ISAT U Scholarship Application and Ranking System	The increasing demand for scholarships at Iloilo Science and Technology\r\nUniversity (ISAT U) has highlighted the limitations of manual, fragmented scholarship\r\napplication processes. Students often face challenges in accessing information, applying\r\nefficiently, and tracking the status of their applications.\r\nTo address these issues, the researchers developed "SKOLAR KONEK: ISAT U\r\nScholarship Application and Ranking System", a web-based platform that simplifies and\r\ndigitizes the entire scholarship management process. The system enables students to\r\nregister, apply, and receive recommendations for scholarships, while sponsors can post\r\nopportunities, review applications, and automatically generate applicant rankings based on\r\npredefined criteria.\r\nThe system was developed using the prototyping methodology, which involved\r\niterative phases of planning, analysis, design, testing, and refinement. It incorporates\r\nautomated functions such as document submission, eligibility filtering, and real-time status\r\ntracking. ISO 25010 software quality standards were applied for evaluation, with results\r\nfrom IT experts and student users indicating excellent ratings across usability,\r\nfunctionality, performance, and security.	BSIT	St. John T. Dignadice, Felix. E. Oros, Karl Virgil M. Palma, Earl John.M. Sombiro, Mhia C. Torremoro	["Web-based platform","Student registration","Scholarship application submission","Automated document submission","Eligibility filtering","Real-time status tracking","Scholarship opportunity posting","Automatic applicant ranking"]
30	SILENT VOICE: FILIPINO SIGN LANGUAGE TRANSLATOR SOFTWARE	Hearing loss affects over 1.7 million individuals in the Philippines, creating\r\nsignificant communication barriers between the deaf and hearing communities. Filipino\r\nSign Language (FSL) is the primary language of the deaf, yet many hearing individuals\r\nlack the proficiency to communicate, leading to challenges in accessibility and inclusion.\r\nExisting sign language translation tools primarily support English and rely on static image\r\nrecognition, failing to capture the real-time dynamic hand gestures used in natural\r\nconversations. This limitation restricts effective communication and excludes many\r\nFilipino deaf individuals from meaningful interactions. To address this issue, this study\r\ndeveloped a web-based Filipino Sign Language Translator capable of recognizing and\r\ntranslating dynamic FSL gestures into words. The system employs a MediaPipe-Long\r\nShort-Term Memory hybrid model, where MediaPipe extracts real-time hand landmarks,\r\nand Long Short-Term Memory networks classify sequential hand gestures. The system’s\r\naccuracy was evaluated using the F1 Score, achieving a weighted average of 0.91,\r\ndemonstrating high precision and reliability in gesture recognition.	BSIT	Jacklord T. Española, Drake Francis M. Jaculina, Jessa Mae G. Mirabuena, Renz Emmanuel S. Pabalinas, Ben Robert T. Salve	["Real-time hand landmark extraction","Dynamic gesture recognition","MediaPipe integration","Long Short-Term Memory classification","Web-based translation interface"]
31	DEVELOPMENT OF ENVIROLINK: A ENVIRONMENTAL CROWDSOURCING PLATFORM	The environmental engagement gap in the Philippines poses a significant challenge, limiting effective participation in sustainability initiatives and reducing community impact. The study, "Development of EnviroLink: An Environmental Crowdsourcing Platform," addresses this issue. It is a web-based platform that connects Campaign Managers, Volunteers, and Administrators through an automated campaign management system. EnviroLink enables Campaign Managers to create detailed campaign profiles including objectives and locations, while allowing Volunteers to join based on their interests and Administrators to oversee approvals. The system ensures efficient coordination by aligning campaign needs with volunteer capabilities using a structured process for campaign creation and submission. The system was developed using the Extreme Programming Agile Methodology. Campaign Managers, Volunteers, and IT experts evaluated it using ISO 25010 standards, achieving a "Very Satisfactory" rating (mean 4.50). The system enhances environmental participation, reduces administrative burdens, and improves campaign efficiency. This study provides a scalable solution to boost environmental engagement in the Philippines, with potential applications for future research and sustainability platforms.	BSIT	Dean Floyd P. Gevero, EJ G. Delgado, Danielle Iancy S. Deorico, Jerrick Mitz T. Escosalan, Reynaldo H. Ilangos	["Automated campaign management","Campaign profile creation","Volunteer interest matching","Administrator approval system","Web-based platform"]
32	DEVELOPMENT OF IJOMA: A PORTAL-TYPE JOB-MATCHING SYSTEM	The job-skills mismatch in the Philippines poses a significant challenge, contributing to unemployment and underemployment by creating barriers to effective job placement. The study, "Development of IJOMA: A Portal-Type Job-Matching System", addresses this issue. It is a web-based platform that connects job seekers with employers through an automated job-matching recommendation system. IJOMA (I Job Match) enables job seekers to create detailed profiles including personal details, education, skills, and experience, while allowing employers to customize job postings with weighted criteria. The system ensures precise matching by aligning job seeker qualifications with employer requirements by utilizing advanced techniques such as Sentence-BERT, fuzzy logic, and a two-layer weighting process. The system was developed using the Extreme Programming Agile Methodology. Job seekers, employers, and IT experts evaluated it using ISO 25010 standards, achieving a "Very Satisfactory" rating (mean 4.26). The system improves recruitment, reduces mismatches, and enhances job search efficiency. This study provides a scalable solution to improve job matching in the Philippines, with potential applications for future research and recruitment platforms.	BSIT	BJ Louisse P. Jagolino, Samuel John C. Cerdanio, Paul S. Catalan, Cyril A. Dosado	["Automated job-matching recommendation","Detailed job seeker profiles","Employer-customizable weighted criteria","Sentence-BERT integration","Fuzzy logic matching","Two-layer weighting process"]
63	FARMING TOOLS AND EQUIPMENT RENTAL SYSTEM	Access to modern agricultural tools and equipment remains a significant barrier for\r\nsmallholder and aspiring farmers, particularly in rural areas where financial constraints\r\nlimit the ability to purchase such resources outright. This study was conducted to address\r\nthe gap by developing the Farming Tools and Equipment Rental System, which offers an\r\naffordable and efficient platform for renting farm machinery and tools. The rationale\r\nbehind this project was rooted in the growing need to democratize access to\r\nmechanization, thereby supporting agricultural productivity and sustainability. The\r\nprimary objective of the study was to design and evaluate an online rental system that\r\nallows users to manage accounts, equipment listings, bookings, and payments, while also\r\ngenerating reports to support decision-making. Specifically, the system aimed to manage\r\nusers effectively, handle booking and payments securely, organize tools and equipment\r\ndata, generate reports for operational insights, and evaluate system performance through\r\nUser Acceptance Testing (UAT).	BSIS	Ken Maro J. Saenz, Patrick John B. Catalan, Leian Rey L. Lagos	["User account management","Equipment listings management","Booking handling","Payment processing","Report generation","User Acceptance Testing"]
33	PADAYON: A DEVELOPMENT OF AI APPLICATION FOR HILIGAYNON SPEAKERS WITH EMOTION RECOGNITION	Mental health remains a critical global concern, particularly for individuals facing\r\nemotional challenges who are further hindered by linguistic and cultural barriers in\r\naccessing professional care. In the Philippines, the lack of regionally inclusive mental\r\nhealth support systems poses challenges for Hiligaynon-speaking users. This study\r\nintroduced Padayon, a web-based AI application designed to provide emotion-aware\r\nmental health support through culturally sensitive chatbot interactions. The system\r\nintegrates Natural Language Processing (NLP) for text-based emotion recognition and\r\nDeepFace for facial expression analysis, enabling real-time detection of user emotions\r\nthrough both textual and visual inputs.\r\nThe system was developed using the Extreme Programming (XP) methodology,\r\nemphasizing iterative development phases including planning, design, coding, and release.\r\nA purposive sampling technique was employed to select twenty (n = 20) respondents,\r\ncomprising Hiligaynon speakers, IT professionals, students, and mental health\r\npractitioners. The system's software quality was evaluated using the ISO 25010 Software\r\nQuality Standards, covering eight quality characteristics.\r\nThe emotion recognition model achieved a weighted average F1-Score of 0.86,\r\nindicating a high level of accuracy and consistency in detecting user emotions. While the\r\noverall software quality evaluation yielded an average mean score of 4.39, rated as “Very\r\nSatisfactory.” High scores in Security (M=4.75), Compatibility (M=4.60), and Flexibility\r\n(M=4.53) confirmed the application's robustness, adaptability, and secure performance.\r\nUser feedback reflected positive reception in terms of usability, reliability, and\r\nemotional responsiveness Results indicated that Padayon effectively recognized user\r\nemotions, delivered contextually appropriate responses, and achieved high user satisfaction\r\nrates. Thus, this study demonstrates the potential of AI-driven solutions in enhancing\r\nemotional support services for underrepresented language groups, fostering emotional\r\nresilience and well-being through an innovative, user-centered approach.	BSIT	Jasmin Mae G. Mamon, Neil Francis N. Navarro, Vincent A. Pastor, Lance Y. Sarabia	["Text-based emotion recognition","Facial expression analysis","Real-time emotion detection","Culturally sensitive chatbot","Natural Language Processing integration","DeepFace integration"]
34	BUZZING BEEQUEST: A WEB-BASED PIXEL ADVENTURE	This study focuses on the design, development, and evaluation of Buzzing Bee Quest: A Web-Based Pixel Adventure, an educational game aimed at enhancing fourth-grade students’ engagement and performance in English, Science, and Math. The game integrates gamification and pixel art design to create a fun, interactive learning environment aligned with curriculum standards.\r\nDeveloped using web technologies and evaluated based on ISO 25010 standards, the game was assessed across key software quality attributes, including Usability, Performance Efficiency, Compatibility, Reliability, Security, Maintainability, and Portability. Evaluation results indicated high user satisfaction, with average ratings interpreted as Excellent, particularly in Usability (4.35), Performance Efficiency (4.28), and Security (4.38).\r\nThe game features random level generation, scoring systems, progress tracking, and curriculum-aligned challenges designed to support cognitive development and boost student motivation. The findings affirm the effectiveness of gamified learning tools in enhancing educational engagement and improving learning outcomes.\r\nRecommendations for future development include integrating reward systems, diverse playable characters, interactive maps, and level-based progression. This research contributes to the growing field of educational gamification, providing a dynamic platform that fosters 21st-century learning skills in elementary education.	BSIT	Daisyrey P. Mecinas, Joseph Rex E. Deocampo, Liane Marie B. Opeña, Hannah Nicole S. Lacdo-o, Jomel G. Antiqueña, Brijs M. Tan	["Random level generation","Scoring systems","Progress tracking","Curriculum-aligned challenges","Gamification elements","Pixel art design"]
35	IoT – INTEGRATED AND DRIP IRRIGATION AND GROWTH MONITORING SYSTEM FOR TOMATO PLANT	The IoT-Integrated Drip Irrigation and Growth Monitoring System for Tomato Plant is designed to improve crop productivity whether it is planted on or off season. Its primary goal is to develop a system that automates the water distribution and growth monitoring using IoT systems for greenhouse tomato crop. Diamante Max (Solanum lycopersicum.), locally known as kamatis is one of the most profitable crops for off season production preferably from May to September. However, farmers here in the Philippines currently do not invest in technological advancements that could help in the production and stick to traditional planting instead. Addressing this gap, the researchers develop a study specifically for off season farming that uses greenhouse farming. It has a system that can monitor the plant growth, detect soil moisture as well as soil macronutrient (NPK) and automates drip irrigation that can be beneficial for maximum production of tomato plants. It includes a custom web-based application that provides a user-friendly interface for monitoring real time updates from the sensors. It has added features where the user can receive notification and updates via email. It has an added feature wherein data can be exported to PDF and CSV file. The study was built using C++ for the microcontroller and javascript programming language for the software and followed Prototyping Model. The system was evaluated using ISO 25010 standards resulting in "Excellent" with an average rate of 4.80 as rated by one (1) General User, two (2) Agriculturist, three (3) Students, and four (4) IT Professional. This implies the overall excellence of the system in catering the needs of tomato plants demonstrating its potential as a reliable and effective solution for improving the production of tomato plants.	BSIT	Nalaza, Wendy E., Porras, Dorlyne Fate S., Salaber, Naomi Ruth D., Siatan, Floreda Mae H.	["Plant growth monitoring","Soil moisture detection","Soil macronutrient (NPK) detection","Automated drip irrigation","Real-time sensor updates","Email notification system","Data export to PDF and CSV"]
36	GUPPY SHOW MANAGEMENT SYSTEM	The Guppy Show Management System is a web-based platform designed to streamline the process of managing and participating in events. The system provided a comprehensive solution for both organizers and contestants by offering tools for event creation, entry submission, and payment processing. This platform aimed to enhance user experience through a user-friendly interface that facilitates efficient event management.\r\nThe system allowed event organizers to create and manage events, invite participants, and categorize entries. Contestants can upload their entries in multiple categories and process payments directly within the platform. Additionally, the system offered features to evaluate entries and interact with posted results through comments and likes, promoting engagement and feedback.	BSIT	Eduardo L. Ontanillas Jr., Joseph Timothy D. Villalobos, Al Christian B. Magno, Joyce Ann P. Cornel	["Event creation and management","Entry submission","Payment processing","Entry categorization","Entry evaluation","Comments and likes interaction"]
37	SMARTPARK:REAL-TIME PARKING AVAILABILITYSYSTEM	The persistent challenge of inefficient parking management on university campuses frequently leads tofrustration among drivers and a waste oftheirvaluable time. To address the specific parking difficulties encountered at Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT U), this capstone project developed SmartPark, a web application delivering real-time information regarding parking availability. By employing a systems prototyping approach and utilizing Raspberry Pi devices for camera-driven detection of parking space occupancy, SmartPark offers users an easily understandable, color-coded real-time view of parking options and equips administrators with effective tools for oversight. Main functionalities of the system include a real-time display of the parking map, automated identification of occupied parking spaces, recording of parking duration, comprehensive administrative tools for users and parking areas, violation notifications, and report generation capabilities. Evaluated against the ISO 25010 standard using input from individuals associated with ISAT U, SmartPark achieved an overall "Excellent" rating (mean 4.40). This positive feedback indicates that SmartPark could greatly enhance the parking experience at ISAT U. Future efforts should aim to make vehicle detection more accurate, improve the system's performance, add features that meet user needs, and makethesystem more adaptable for different situations.	BSIT	JoshVincent S. Projillo, FrankElmorG. Hontarciego, Bhea T. Talibo, KristineJoy O.Garnica, AngelaFreda Marie Feliciano	["Real-time parking map display","Camera-driven parking space detection","Automated occupied space identification","Parking duration recording","Administrative user management","Parking area management tools","Violation notification system","Report generation capabilities"]
38	AndroidBasedVoting System	TheAndroid Based Voting System was developed to beusedin Iloilo Science and Technology University forthe convenienceof voters during theelection. Thesystem is designed to help thevoters to cast votes easily. The proposed system isan android application that uses fingerprint forauthentication. Thesystem can tally votes automatically, andtheresult cannot be manipulated bytheadministrator. Thesystem users consistsof theadministratorwhowill beableto view and updatetheinformation ofall thecandidates, partylist, organization,election and the voter’sinformation.Theadministratorwill betheone torestore all theinformation in the system storage. v Thesystem send an SMSnotification containing theiraccount and password before theelection period. During this, theusers willbe needto log in to theirmobile devices tovote and thesystem will requiretheir fingerprint tobe scanned for verification. Thesystem will automatically showtheresult after theelection period and theuser will receiveanother SMSnotification forthefinal result ofelection. The researchers tested the system wherein the selected users will do an evaluation. TheAndroid Based Voting System was tested using theblack boxand whiteboxtesting which tested all the qualityrequirements ofthe system. Purposivesampling was usedin theselection of therespondents based onISO 25010.	BSIT	Jerlyn MaeP. Sanchez, Kimberly G. Ganila, JonnaC. Naysayo, NiñoF. Romero	["Fingerprint authentication","Automatic vote tallying","Administrator information management","SMS notification for account details","SMS notification for election results","Mobile device login","Vote verification via fingerprint scan","Black box testing","White box testing"]
39	SAILO: DEVELOPMENT OF TICKETING SYSTEM FOR POINT TO POINT FERRY BOAT TERMINALS	This study presents the development of Sailo: A Ticketing System for Point-to- Point Ferry Boat Terminals, a web-based and mobile version designed to automate and enhance the ferry ticketing process between Iloilo and Guimaras. Traditional ticketing methods result in long queues, limited payment options, and inefficient data management, leading to operational challenges for ferry operators. Sailo addresses these issues by enabling passengers to book tickets online, make secure payments using a digital credit system, and generate tickets with QR codes for smooth verification at terminals. The system also automates terminal management, booking transactions, passenger verification, report generation, and to evaluate based on ISO 25010 Quality Standards, ensuring its compliance with Functional Suitability, Reliability, Usability, Performance, Efficiency, Security, Compatibility, Maintainability, and Portability. The researchers used the purposive sampling technique to select respondents who have the knowledge about the system. There are twenty (20) composed of; Terminal Admin, Ticket Agent and Ferry Operators and fifty (50) Passengers for both Guimaras and Iloilo, and two (2) IT Experts who served as respondents of the system. The findings revealed that the system satisfied all the objectives that were mentioned above. The results of the evaluation show that the overall average score was 4.39. This rating falls under the category of "Excellent." This means that the system has successfully met the quality standards based on the ISO 25010 model. In other words, the system performs very well in terms of quality, and it meets the expectations for a high-quality software product. The high score indicates that users are very satisfied with the system’s features, functions, and overall performance.	BSIT	Angie Mae M. Sombiro, CJ E. Velasco, Michael John P. Senope, Ricardo E. Porras III, Sean Edrian Suarez	["Online ticket booking","Digital credit payment system","QR code ticket generation","Terminal management automation","Booking transaction processing","Passenger verification","Report generation"]
40	ARchive: A MOBILE APPLICATION OF ISAT U CAMPUS USING YOLO ALGORITHM	ISAT U has a rich history dating back 116 years, yet many students, particularly freshmen, struggle to connect with its legacy. This disconnect may affect their sense of belonging, engagement, and appreciation of the university’s heritage. To address this issue, this study presents ARchive: A Mobile Application of ISAT U Campus using YOLO Algorithm, an AR-based campus tour guide designed to provide an immersive and interactive exploration of ISAT U’s history and landmarks. By overlaying digital content onto real-world environments, the application enhances student engagement and facilitates a deeper connection to the institution.\r\nThe system utilizes the YOLO algorithm for object identification, ensuring accurate recognition of campus buildings. Performance evaluation was conducted using accuracy, precision, demonstrating high effectiveness in detecting and overlaying digital information. Additionally, the system was assessed using ISO 25010 software quality standards, ensuring functionality, usability, and performance efficiency. The findings confirm that ARchive provides an innovative and automated solution for guiding students through the university, fostering institutional pride, and enhancing the overall campus experience.	BSCS	Kier John B. Agravante, Nicole Ashley E. Cerbo, Kenneth M. Doctor	["YOLO object identification","AR-based campus tour","Digital content overlay","Campus building recognition","Performance evaluation metrics"]
41	TRADEANSBOT: A Chatbot Mobile Application For ISAT University Utilizing RAG-Sequence Model	This study presents Tradeansbot in a time where rapid and reliable information accessibility is crucial. an artificial intelligence (AI) powered chatbot smartphone application created for Iloilo Science and Technology (ISAT-U) that offers precise, real-time answers to questions about university. With the help of ChromaDB, a vector database that facilitates effective information retrieval via vector embeddings and cosine similarity, TRADEANSBOT incorporates OpenAI's GPT-based language model for natural language interpretation and answer creation. LangChain, which organizes the communication between the language model and the document retriever, is used to process user inputs. FastAPI, a high-performance web framework, is used in the development of the backend to manage real-time communication between the server and mobile application. Supabase is employed for student account authentication and data management, ensuring secure and personalized access. With Supabase handling real-time data and user authentication, the application was developed with Flutter for the mobile interface and FastAPI for backend processing. The integration of external data and query flow were also coordinated using LangChain. The system was evaluated using the ISO 25010 software quality model, focusing on criteria such as functionality, usability, reliability, performance efficiency, maintainability, security, and portability. Evaluation results from IT professionals and users demonstrated that TRADEANSBOT performed excellently in most areas, highlighting its potential to serve as a dependable academic support tool.	BSCS	Kevyn A. Alojepan, Joyce Mae R. Jurado, Elicher D. Satumbaga	["Vector database retrieval","GPT-based language model","LangChain input processing","FastAPI backend communication","Supabase authentication","Flutter mobile interface","Real-time data handling","External data integration"]
42	SandBlock: Real Time Screen Monitoring System for Parental Control and Digital Safety using Yolov8 Algorithm	The rapid advancement of digital technology has brought about significant improvements in\r\nvarious domains, but it has also led to challenges in ensuring digital safety, particularly in\r\nmonitoring and filtering inappropriate content to vulnerable populations. Digital safety for\r\nchildren has become increasingly important as the internet and mobile devices play a central role\r\nin their lives. The convenience and accessibility of the internet offer numerous educational and\r\nrecreational opportunities, but they also expose children to various risks, including inappropriate\r\nsexual content, cyberbully, and online predators.\r\nThis study aims to develop that could cater this gap through an innovative approach to digital\r\nsafety. Using the YOLOv8 algorithm, this real-time screen monitoring solution specifically\r\ntargets image-based content, providing more accurate detection of\r\niv\r\ninappropriate material than conventional static filters. Hence, the researchers have developed the\r\nSandblock: Real Time Screen Monitoring System for Parental Control and Digital Safety using\r\nYolov8 Algorithm to address this concern.\r\nFurther, the study has proved efficiency of the the Sandblock: Real Time Screen Monitoring\r\nSystem for Parental Control and Digital Safety using Yolov8 Algorithm in a survey conducted\r\nby the researchers for IT experts and ISAT U students after garnering a total mean of 4.18,\r\ndescribed as excellence on the ISO 25010 Standards in terms of reliability, portability, usability,\r\nperformance efficiency, and maintainability.	BSCS	CHLOE LOUISE O. APOSAGA, TRISHA LOUIE O. ESPINAL, ROLYN JOHN M. GRANADA, ZYRA MARIE T. ROSAL	["Real-time screen monitoring","YOLOv8 image detection","Parental control alerts","Inappropriate content filtering"]
43	ONEUP: CONVERTING 2D IMAGES INTO 3D MODELS THROUGH DIGITAL IMAGE PROCESSING	The transition from two-dimensional (2D) to three-dimensional (3D) representation marks a significant advancement in the field of image processing, enabling enhanced visualization and analysis across various industries. However, the complexity and steep learning curve associated with existing 3D modeling software often limit its accessibility to experts, leaving behind educators, beginners, and small businesses who require simpler tools. Additionally, a vast repository of 2D images remains underutilized due to the lack of efficient methods for converting them into 3D models. This study addresses the challenge of generating accurate 3D representations from a single 2D image through digital image processing techniques. The proposed system integrates thresholding-based background removal, monocular depth estimation, and mesh generation algorithms to automate the 2D-to-3D conversion process. By eliminating the need for specialized hardware or extensive technical knowledge, the system aims to democratize 3D modeling and cater to a broader range of users. The research further evaluates the system’s performance using the ISO 25010 software quality standards, ensuring its reliability, usability, and effectiveness. Ultimately, this study contributes to the development of accessible 3D modeling solutions, expanding opportunities for innovation in fields such as education, rapid prototyping, and 3D printing.	BSCS	LHIL JOHN BADIANGO, LARRY DENVER D. BIACO, LOU VAN ERICK M. PIANSAY	["Thresholding-based background removal","Monocular depth estimation","Mesh generation algorithms","2D-to-3D conversion automation"]
44	WEB-BASED ENTITY RELATIONSHIP DIAGRAM (ERD) AND SQL SCHEMA GENERATOR USING REGEX AND DECISION TREE ALGORITHM	As database technologies continue to evolve, designing databases efficiently and\r\naccurately has become more important than ever. At the heart of this process is the\r\nEntity-Relationship Diagram (ERD), which helps users visualize how data is structured\r\nand connected. Yet, manually creating ERDs and writing the corresponding SQL\r\nschemas can be a tedious task, often prone to mistakes.\r\nThis study presents a web-based system that simplifies and automates the creation\r\nof ERDs and SQL scripts. By using regular expressions (Regex) along with a decision\r\ntree algorithm, the system can understand user-defined table names and intelligently\r\ndetermine the necessary entities, attributes, and relationships. It then generates a visual\r\nER diagram along with the matching SQL code.\r\nThe main aim of this tool was to make the database design process faster, more\r\naccurate, and consistent. It has designed to work with different database management\r\nv\r\nsystems and was especially helpful for students, educators, and researchers who want to\r\nfocus more on learning data structures without getting bogged down by technical details.\r\nTo ensure quality, the system was evaluated based on the ISO 25010 software\r\nquality model, paying close attention to how well it functions, how easy it is to use, and\r\nhow reliable it is in practice.\r\nTo enhance its potential, future improvements are recommended, including\r\nsupport for multimedia inputs, business rule interpretation, automatic normalization,\r\nimproved user guidance, and a modernized interface. These enhancements aim to\r\nbroaden its usability and strengthen its role as a versatile tool for database design.	BSCS	Mary Joy G. Batchar, Nilo D. Carpo IV, Hannah N. Fabillo	["Regex-based entity recognition","Decision tree algorithm","Visual ER diagram generation","SQL code generation","User-defined table name parsing","Multi-database management support"]
45	PSEUDOFLOW: A FLOWCHART TO PSEUDOCODE TO C – CODE WEB APPLICATION CONVERTER	This study, understanding the logical flow of programs is critical in programming education, yet the manual conversion from flowcharts to pseudocode and C code remains a challenge for many learners. Existing tools offer partial solutions, often lacking structured transitions or educational support, which hampers comprehension. This study addresses these limitations by developing Pseudoflow, a web-based application that converts flowcharts into pseudocode and then into C code using a Rule-Based Algorithm. The system features a user-friendly drag-and-drop interface for constructing flowcharts, which are validated and processed to ensure logical accuracy before transformation. Developed with HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, the application applies predefined logical rules to automate the conversion process. The project follows a throw-away prototyping methodology and integrates both white-box and black-box testing for validation. System evaluation, based on ISO 25010 quality standards and feedback from ICT experts and first-year computer science students, rated the application as "Excellent" in Functional Suitability and Interaction Capability. Findings show that Pseudoflow significantly aids beginners in understanding algorithm structure and logic, improving programming fluency. The study concludes that combining visual programming with rule-based automation can bridge educational gaps in programming instruction. It is recommended that future development extend support for additional programming languages, data types, and logic structures to enhance versatility and learning outcomes.	BSCS	Jhereed Michael M. Bolivar, Joshua C. Bundac, Vince N. Javier	["Drag-and-drop interface","Flowchart validation","Rule-Based Algorithm conversion","Pseudocode generation","C code generation","Logical accuracy checking","White-box testing","Black-box testing"]
46	Mobile ASL Interpreter using CNN-based algorithms	Communication barriers between individuals with hearing impairments and non-signers pose significant challenges in daily interactions. This study presents the development of a Mobile ASL Interpreter using CNN-based algorithms, a mobile application designed to translate American Sign Language (ASL) into English text. The application leverages Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Mediapipe solutions to recognize and interpret ASL gestures from pre-recorded video files. Unlike existing desktop-based solutions, this application offers an offline mobile experience, making it more accessible and practical for real-world use.\r\nThe study followed a prototyping methodology, ensuring iterative refinement through user feedback and software quality evaluation based on ISO 25010 standards. The system was tested by ICT experts, SPED professionals, and students, evaluating functionality, performance efficiency, usability, and user experience. Results indicated a high level of accuracy in gesture recognition and translation, with users rating the system as “Excellent” in key quality metrics.\r\nThe findings demonstrate the application’s potential to bridge communication gaps for individuals with hearing impairments. Future enhancements may include real-time gesture recognition, multilingual support, and cloud-based synchronization. This study contributes to the advancement of assistive technologies, fostering more inclusive and effective communication for ASL users in various social and professional settings.	BSCS	John Doe	["CNN-based gesture recognition","Mediapipe integration","Offline mobile application","Pre-recorded video processing","ASL to English translation"]
47	PRISM: A Library Book Recommendation System Using Collaborative Filtering and Content-Based Filtering Hybrid Algorithm	Digital libraries offer significant advantages over traditional libraries by providing\r\nefficient access to digital resources. However, current search methods in digital libraries\r\noften face challenges such as information overload and inefficiency in retrieving relevant\r\nresources. Traditional keyword-based search techniques are limited in providing\r\npersonalized, contextually relevant results. This problem is particularly evident in\r\neducational settings where students and faculty require more accurate and tailored\r\nrecommendations for their research needs.\r\nThis study aims to address these limitations by developing an AI-powered library\r\nbook recommendation system for the Iloilo Science and Technology University (ISAT-\r\nU) library. The proposed system combines collaborative filtering and content-based\r\nfiltering algorithms, enhanced with natural language processing (NLP), to provide\r\npersonalized book recommendations based on user queries and preferences. By\r\nleveraging these advanced techniques, the system will not only improve the accuracy of\r\nsearch results but also reduce information overload for users.\r\nThe study will develop a system that manages user accounts and book\r\nrecommendations, implements a hybrid recommendation algorithm using collaborative\r\nfiltering and content-based filtering, and evaluates the system’s performance using ISO\r\n25010 standards for quality, including functionality, usability, and reliability. The system\r\nwill also gather user feedback to continuously improve recommendations. The evaluation\r\naims to confirm the system’s effectiveness in enhancing resource discoverability and user\r\nsatisfaction.\r\nBy addressing the current limitations of digital library search methods, this study\r\naims to provide a scalable solution that improves the overall user experience, making it\r\neasier for users to find relevant resources efficiently.	BSCS	Shan Kian R. Buenafe, Francis Ivan B. Narandan, Leah Grace G. Salongcong	["Collaborative filtering algorithm","Content-based filtering algorithm","Hybrid recommendation algorithm","Natural language processing","User account management","Book recommendation management","User feedback collection"]
48	VIDEO CONTENT FILTERING OF EXPLICIT CONTENT USING 3D RESNET AND BILSTM ALGORITHM	The rapid proliferation of digital media has increased concerns about the exposure\r\nof individuals, particularly children, to inappropriate content. To address this issue, this\r\nstudy proposes the development of a Video Content Filtering System Using ResNet and\r\nBiLSTM Algorithm. The system is designed to detect and filter explicit content,\r\nspecifically profanity in audio and kissing scenes in video, ensuring a safer viewing\r\nexperience for users.\r\nThe audio filtering module utilizes Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory\r\n(BiLSTM) and Bidirectional Encoder Representations from Transformers (BERT) to\r\nidentify profane words from speech. The system employs speech recognition technology\r\nto convert spoken words into text, which is then processed to detect offensive language.\r\nv\r\nOnce detected, the explicit segments are bleeped to prevent inappropriate audio content\r\nfrom being heard.\r\nThe video filtering module integrates 3D ResNet-18, a pre-trained deep learning\r\nmodel, to analyze video frames and identify kissing scenes. The detected explicit frames\r\nare blurred, ensuring that inappropriate visual content is obscured while maintaining the\r\nnatural flow of the video.\r\nTo evaluate the system’s performance, accuracy and F1-score were used as key\r\nmetrics. The results demonstrate that the BiLSTM + BERT model for profanity detection\r\nachieves high accuracy in identifying explicit words, while the 3D ResNet-18 model\r\neffectively detects and blurs kissing scenes. The system was also assessed using ISO\r\n25010 software quality standards, ensuring functionality, usability, and performance\r\nefficiency. The profanity detection component demonstrated strong performance\r\nachieving an accuracy of 90% and a F1-score of 90%, while the kissing detection\r\ncomponent achieved promising results, achieving an accuracy of 79% and a F1-score of\r\n84%. These findings suggest effective capabilities in automated video content moderation\r\nfor explicit content.\r\nThe researchers concludes that the developed system provides an effective and\r\nautomated solution for filtering explicit content in videos. Future enhancements may\r\ninclude multilingual support for profanity detection and improved contextual\r\nunderstanding of explicit content.	BSCS	Myka Joyce C. Cadungog, Akari S. Deamboy, Renz Andrei M. Ibañez	["Profanity detection with BiLSTM","Speech recognition to text","Explicit audio segment bleeping","3D ResNet-18 video frame analysis","Kissing scene detection","Blurring of explicit video frames"]
49	AbTech: A Rescue App for Instantaneous Emergency Response and First Aid Station Connectivity using Dijkstra’s Algorithm	Road traffic accidents are a leading cause of fatalities and injuries worldwide, often worsened by delayed emergency responses. This study introduces an automated accident detection and alert system using smartphones to reduce response times and casualties. The system monitors speed and location data to detect sudden changes indicative of a crash and triggers alerts to the nearest responders using Dijkstra’s algorithm for optimal routing.\r\nDijkstra’s algorithm is used to find the fastest way to get help to the accident site. It works by creating a map where places like the accident location, hospitals, and responder stations are shown as points (called nodes), and the roads between them are lines (called edges) with travel times. The algorithm then finds the shortest route from the accident location to the nearest responder.	BSCS	Edianel, Rowel Angelo E., Tabang, Edward Von Josef B., Villaluz, Bea Bianca, May Florence J. Franco	["Accident detection via smartphone sensors","Speed and location monitoring","Automated emergency alert triggering","Dijkstra’s algorithm routing","Mapping of nodes and edges","Optimal route calculation to responders"]
50	TeachAR: An Interactive Learning Mobile Application Using Convolutional Neural Network	The COVID-19 pandemic profoundly disrupted early childhood education, shifting learning from traditional face-to-face instruction to modular and online formats. While students gradually adapted, this transition exacerbated concerns about short attention spans and hyperactivity among young learners. Returning to in-person classes further highlighted these challenges, as teachers struggled to re-engage students accustomed to self-directed, screen-based learning. In response to these issues, this study introduces TeachAR, an interactive learning mobile application that leverages Augmented Reality (AR) and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) to enhance early childhood education.\r\nThe development of TeachAR followed the Throw-away Prototyping SDLC model, which allowed the development team to quickly create a working prototype to gather user feedback and refine the system's functionality and user interface. This iterative approach was instrumental in addressing usability concerns and aligning the application with the needs of its young target users, as well as the expectations of educators and guardians.\r\nFor the intelligent object recognition feature, the YOLO (You Only Look Once) algorithm—specifically the YOLOv5 architecture—was implemented using Python, with deep learning frameworks such as PyTorch to support CNN-based training and real-time educational object detection. These technologies enabled the accurate classification of key learning elements such as letters, numbers, and shapes, which are crucial in early education.\r\nThe system achieves its objectives, with an end evaluation resulting in an overall mean score of 4.6, indicating that the system meets a very high-quality standard according to ISO 25010 International Standards. This underscores TeachAR’s excellent quality and suitability for practical use, affirming its potential to address the attention and engagement challenges faced by young learners in the post-pandemic educational landscape.	BSCS	Divine Joy E. Ermoso, Seanron F. Sotito, Katherine T. Talaman	["Augmented Reality integration","Convolutional Neural Network training","YOLOv5 object recognition","Real-time educational object detection","Classification of letters, numbers, shapes","Interactive learning mobile application","User interface refinement","Prototype user feedback incorporation"]
51	Enhancing Resume Screening Efficiency onMobilePlatforms through Parsing and RankingAlgorithm	In today’sdigital and fast-paced hiring environment, traditional manual resume screening methods havebecome inefficient, time-consuming, and prone tohuman bias. Thisstudy proposes thedevelopment of aResumeScreening System, implemented as a mobile-responsivewebsite, aimed at enhancing the efficiency, fairness, and objectivityof theapplicant evaluation process. Thesystem leverages parsing algorithms toextract structured datafrom PDF resumes and employs Latent SemanticAnalysis (LSA)—a Natural Language Processing (NLP)technique—to assess thesemanticrelevance between applicant qualifications andjob requirements. Through similarityscoring and ranking mechanisms, thesystem evaluates resumes based oneducation, skills,and experience, producing aprioritized listof candidates aligned with predefined job-specific metrics. Designed to streamlinethehiring process for bothemployers and applicants, the platform supports job creation, resume submission, andapplicant ranking in auser-friendly and efficient manner. Thesystem underwent evaluation using the ISO25010 qualitymodel, achieving ahigh overall mean score of4.66,which indicates compliance withinternational software quality standards in areas such as functionality, performance, iv usability, maintainability, and security. The results demonstrate that theproposed system effectively automates and optimizes resume screening onmobileplatforms, making ita practical tool forbusinesses and organizations seeking asmarter, technology-driven recruitment solution.	BSCS	Kyle Owie A. Fernandez, StephanieLauryn P.Cerigo, Mark Cj C. Paclibar	["Parsing algorithms for PDF resumes","Latent Semantic Analysis (LSA)","Similarity scoring mechanism","Applicant ranking system","Job creation support","Resume submission interface","Mobile-responsive website"]
52	VIRTUAL PRIVATE NETWORK (VPN) FOR HOME NETWORK CONNECTION AND REMOTE FILE SHARING USING WIREGUARD PROTOCOL	The Virtual Private Network For Home Network Connection And File Sharing research project presents a system developed by using the Wireguard Protocol to create a virtual private network where devices could route all traffic through a designated egress point and share files among the devices. By employing the NAT Traversal, Port Forwarding and Wireguard Protocols, the system addresses problems in the Philippine Internet Service landscape such as data insecurity, limited and expensive internet and data plans. The system proposes a compelling alternative. A VPN tunnel is established and uses the user's home network to create a secure, encrypted tunnel. Remote users would be able to connect and effectively extend the home network to their location and routing all their internet traffic through the home internet connection and allowing them to access their fil es remotely.	BSCS	Daniel M. Inocencio, John Patrick P. Pasol, John Llyco M. Sauza	["Wireguard Protocol VPN tunnel","NAT Traversal implementation","Port Forwarding capability","Remote file sharing","Encrypted traffic routing"]
53	Dynamic Image Protection:A Web-BasedScript Against AI Scraping andUnauthorizedDownloads	The widespread adoption of digital content-sharing platforms has increased the risks of unauthorized image use, particularly through AI-driven web scraping.Traditional security measures such as watermarking,JavaScript-based restrictions,and legal enforcement have proven insufficient in preventing the extraction and misuse of online images.\r\nUnauthorized image use presents significant disadvantages for content creators,including loss of intellectual property control,diminished revenue opportunities,and dilution of brand value.AI-powered scraping tools can bypass conventional protections,automatically collecting and processing vast amounts of visual data without creator consent.\r\nThis study introduces the Dynamic Image Protection Script (DIPS),a web-based framework designed to safeguard images through multi-layered security mechanisms.DIPS integrates chaotic encryption using a Logistic Map XOR algorithm, JavaScript-based client-side protections(right-click prevention, screenshot blocking), and server-side AI-aware detection (rate limiting, behavioral fingerprinting). Testing demonstrated robust performance,with 94% accuracy in encryption/decryption, 92% effectiveness in blocking AI scrapers, and high user satisfaction ratings.	BSCS	JohnCoolyn R. Jabican,Peter Gabriel R.Lopez, Khenee C.Matanguihan	["Chaotic encryption","Logistic Map XOR algorithm","JavaScript client-side protections","Right-click prevention","Screenshot blocking","Server-side AI-aware detection","Rate limiting","Behavioral fingerprinting"]
64	Web-based Inventory Management System	This software project is a web-based inventory management system for a small business enterprise established in Pagadian City, Zamboanga del Sur, Philippines. It primarily supports the business owner of the said business enterprise to perform regular inventory management online through a web platform. This mechanism did not only improve the overall business process but also enabled the business owner to manage inventories with efficiency and convenience. The enterprise comprises four branches and a mobile store that strolls around the city to cater to customer needs. In addition, the current mechanism of conducting inventory management is purely manual through the use of paper files, which overwhelmed the business owner with several challenges, including data inaccuracy due to the reliance on using papers where data are recorded and process inefficiency due to the manual recording and distribution of inventory and sales reports. This software project addressed these challenges by eliminating these manual approaches through an automated computing solution using a web platform where data are electronically recorded and processed, and reports are electronically produced.	BSIT	Maredel T. Tanaman, Jhon Lloyd A. Baylosis, Bhrnt Joshua A. Abiles, Mark Lester P. Catungal	["Online inventory management","Sales report generation","Warehouse purchase request interface","Dashboard interface","Branch stock request system","Web-based application","Real-time report updates"]
54	ILOCATE: A WEB-BASED BOARDING HOUSE FINDER IN ILOILO CITY USING THE HAVERSINE ALGORITHM	Finding suitable boarding houses remains a common challenge for students and workers relocating to Iloilo City due to limited availability, lack of advertisement, and outdated digital platforms. To address this issue, this study developed ILOcate: A Web-based Boarding House Finder in Iloilo City that helps tenants locate affordable, verified accommodations near their desired location. The system utilizes the Haversine Algorithm to calculate accurate distances between user and boarding house coordinates and integrates Google Maps API to provide real-time geospatial mapping and navigation.\r\nThe application allows landlords to register their properties, including business permit verification, pricing, amenities, photos, and exact GPS location. It also includes administrative features enabling the Iloilo Boarding House Commission to monitor, verify, or close listings, and tenants to file complaints. The system's effectiveness was evaluated using the ISO 25010 software quality model, yielding an overall mean rating of 4.5 (Excellent), while user acceptability testing resulted in a 4.68 overall mean (Excellent), highlighting strong functionality, usability, and performance efficiency.\r\nILOcate serves as a comprehensive digital solution that enhances transparency, accessibility, and user experience in boarding house selection—bridging the gap between tenants and landlords in Iloilo City through reliable map-based services.	BSCS	Edjay C. Lindayao, Abegail Vanjo G. Verdugo, Micah A. Prandas	["Haversine distance calculation","Google Maps API integration","Landlord property registration","Business permit verification","Amenities and photo uploads","GPS location tagging","Administrative listing monitoring","Tenant complaint filing"]
55	School Timetable Generator	The School Timetable Generator research project presents a system developed using Google Sheets and Google Apps Script to automate the scheduling of academic timetables for teachers, sections, and rooms. By employing the First Fit Decreasing (FFD) and Constraint Satisfaction Programming (CSP) algorithms, the system addresses complex scheduling constraints, including teacher availability, room capacity, and subject time sensitivity, while optimizing the allocation of resources. The tool generates conflict-free schedules efficiently, reducing the manual workload and ensuring adherence to academic requirements.\r\nThis system was evaluated using ISO 25010 software quality standards, focusing on functionality, performance, usability, reliability, and security. Results indicate compliance with international standards, achieving an overall rating of "Good" with exceptional performance efficiency and compatibility. Key features include dynamic timetable creation, conflict resolution, and real-time updates within an intuitive interface, ensuring scalability and adaptability to varying institutional needs.\r\nThe research contributes significantly to academic scheduling by providing an efficient, automated solution that minimizes errors, enhances satisfaction among\r\nv\r\neducators and administrators, and establishes a foundation for future enhancements, such as part-time scheduling and backtracking capabilities.	BSCS	Elly Mar E. Tamayor, John Mark S. Jardin, John Dale S. Deocampo, John Emmanuel Grandia	["First Fit Decreasing algorithm","Constraint Satisfaction Programming","Dynamic timetable creation","Conflict resolution","Real-time updates"]
56	E-BAGSAKAN OF AGRICULTURE AND AQUACULTURE BY PRODUCTS	The agricultural and aquaculture industries in the Municipality of Zarraga face challenges in selling products due to intermediaries which results in reducing farmers’ profits. To address this issue, the researchers of the study developed the E-Bagsakan System, an online marketplace that allows farmers to list products, manage orders, and track sales while enabling buyers to browse, purchase, and arrange deliveries conveniently. The E-Bagsakan System aimed to eliminate unnecessary middlemen, ensuring better pricing and efficient transactions. The study was conducted from January 2024 to April 2025. The system was evaluated using the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM) to assess its Perceived Usefulness, Perceived Ease of Use, Attitude to Use, and Behavioral Intention to Use. The result showed that the E-Bagsakan System of Agriculture and Aquaculture by Product was “Strongly Agree” in terms of the Perceived Ease of Use which indicate that the users find the system as easy to access, clear, responsive and minimizes the efforts to complete the tasks. The result showed that the E-Bagsakan System of Agriculture and Aquaculture by Product was “Strongly Agree” in terms of the Attitude to Use which indicate that the users view the system as beneficial, enjoyable, and aligned with their goal and needs. The result showed that the E-Bagsakan System of Agriculture and Aquaculture by Product was “Strongly Agree” in terms of the Behavioral Intention to Use which indicates that the users recognize the value of the system, and actively plan to incorporate the system into their daily tasks. The positive reception indicates that the E-Bagsakan System effectively supports local farmers and consumers of the Municipality of Zarraga by streamlining transactions and improving market accessibility. The results suggest that the system has high potential to be adopted by the users, offering a sustainable solution for the agricultural and aquaculture sectors in Zarraga, Iloilo.	BSIS	Floriden Aura C. Guino-o, Chester Renz S. Galve, Paul Vincent A. Navarro	["Product listing management","Order management","Sales tracking","Buyer browsing interface","Online purchase processing","Delivery arrangement system"]
57	LIBRARY ELECTRONIC RESOURCE ACCESS SYSTEM	The Library Electronic Resource Access System was developed to improve the\r\naccessibility, management, and utilization of digital library resources at Iloilo Science\r\nand Technology University (ISAT U). This system enables students and staff to\r\nefficiently search, view, and access e-books, theses, and online journals via online\r\nresources without the need for physical library visits.\r\nDeveloped using the Prototyping Methodology, the system underwent iterative\r\nrefinement through constant user feedback to ensure responsiveness, usability, and\r\nefficiency. One of the key outcomes of the system is its ability to allow staff to manage\r\nuser accounts, as well as maintain and organize various digital resources including e-\r\nbooks, theses, and subscribed online resource links. Additionally, the system successfully\r\nenables the generation of utilization reports for these resources categorized by college\r\nand month, providing valuable insights into resource usage.\r\nTo assess its usability and user acceptance, the system was evaluated using the\r\nTechnology Acceptance Model (TAM), which measured Perceived Usefulness, Perceived\r\nEase of Use, Attitude Toward Use, and Behavioral Intention. The evaluation results\r\nshowed an overall mean of 4.48 with a standard deviation of 0.58, indicating an\r\n“Excellent” rating across all dimensions and strong positive reception from users.\r\nWith its user-friendly interface, robust management features, the system\r\nsignificantly enhances research productivity and digital resource engagement. Future\r\nenhancements may include advanced search filters, activity logs for staff, and more\r\ndetailed report generation.	BSIS	Jonel A. Encia, Janelle Aubrey E. Magno, Elijah Danielle L. Moral	["User account management","Digital resource organization","E-book access","Thesis access","Online journal access","Utilization report generation","Resource usage categorization"]
58	E-LOCKER: SMART BAGGAGE SOLUTION SYSTEMS	Managing baggage in high-traffic areas such as malls and transport terminals poses challenges, including limited space, security concerns, and slow manual processes. This study presents the E-Locker: Smart Baggage Solution Systems, a web-based platform designed to automate baggage storage using QR code verification, real-time locker tracking, and online payments to simplify drop-off and retrieval. The system was developed using HTML, CSS, Bootstrap, PHP, and MySQL and deployed online via Hostinger. Evolutionary Prototyping guided the system’s iterative development, allowing improvements based on user’s feedback. A total of 35 respondents—30 customers, 2 local supermarket staff, and 3 IT experts—evaluated the system. User acceptance and usability were assessed through the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM) and the System Usability Scale (SUS). The SUS score of 64.93 indicated a need to improve the user interface. Normality testing using the Shapiro-Wilk test showed that most variables were not normally distributed. As a result, Spearman’s rho correlation was applied, revealing strong relationships between perceived usefulness, ease of use, and behavioral intention. Notably, Attitude Toward Use (ATU) and Behavioral Intention (BI) showed a strong correlation (ρ = 0.810). Overall, the E-Locker system enhances convenience, improves security, and provides a scalable solution for modern baggage management.	BSIS	Emmanuel F. Libradilla, Ace Marvin Jay N. Amable, Nestor M. Atchicoso, Jr.	["QR code verification","Real-time locker tracking","Online payments","Web-based platform","User feedback integration"]
59	TICKETING SYSTEM	The study concisely addresses the inefficiencies in the manual ticketing process for\r\npassengers traveling between Guimaras and Parola, which cause delays and inconvenience,\r\nparticularly for students and daily commuters. The study aims to develop an automated\r\nticketing system which met the following objectives such as allowing users to manage\r\naccount which offers online cash-in; manage payment; and admin can manage users, ferry,\r\nrecords, and reports. Using a system development approach, surveys and direct\r\nobservations were conducted to identify user needs. The automated system was designed\r\nand tested on various criteria from the ISO 25010 quality model. The functionality,\r\nusability, maintainability, and portability were assessed as Very Satisfactory indicating\r\nstrong performance in these areas. Performance efficiency, compatibility, security, and\r\nreliability were rated as Satisfactory demonstrating a reliable and efficient system. The\r\noverall assessment classified the system as Very Satisfactory, highlighting its effectiveness\r\nin meeting quality standards. The findings reveal that the new system significantly reduces\r\nprocessing times, improves passenger experience, and enhances data accuracy, allowing\r\niii\r\npassengers to check balances, reload funds, and access tickets more efficiently. The study\r\nconcludes that an automated ticketing system is essential for modernizing transport\r\noperations, reducing manual workload, and enhancing service efficiency. Future research\r\ncould explore mobile application integration and AI-based optimizations for a more\r\nseamless ticketing experience.	BSIS	Vonn Elvis B. Gayas, Philip John C. Mallo, Oemor Ross Joerwin G. Villanueva	["Online cash-in management","Payment management","User account management","Admin user management","Ferry management","Records management","Reports management"]
60	iShop: A Web-based Inventory and Order Management System for SME-Supplier Collaboration and Decision-Making	Small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) face challenges in managing inventory, processing orders, and making timely decisions due to manual processes and limited access to real-time data. This study developed iShop, a web-based inventory and order management system designed to enhance SME–supplier collaboration. iShop was developed using the Agile development methodology, implemented through incremental iterations that prioritized essential functionalities such as user management, inventory tracking, order and payment processing, and report generation via dashboard-based analytics. Built with PHP, MySQL, JavaScript, and HTML/CSS, the system was deployed locally using XAMMP, ensuring compatibility within SME store environments. System usability and user acceptance were evaluated using the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM). Data was collected through a 5-point Likert scale survey completed by thirty (30) participants, including SME owners, suppliers, and IT experts. The results showed “Strongly Agree” across all TAM constructs (Mean=4.23), indicating user satisfaction, improved accuracy, and reduced manual workload. Overall, the evaluation highlighted that iShop has the potential to significantly enhance SME operations and serve as a scalable solution for digital transformation in local business environments.	BSIS	Elaine Faith Gayo, Joshua B. Ballesta, Stefan Kate T. Digdigan	["User management","Inventory tracking","Order processing","Payment processing","Dashboard-based analytics"]
61	CURRICULUM MANAGEMENT SYSTEM FOR DECISION SUPPORT	The Curriculum Management System for Decision Support was developed to\r\nsupport the curriculum planning and monitoring needs of Iloilo Science and Technology\r\nUniversity (ISAT U). The system provides students with an accessible platform to view\r\ntheir program’s curriculum, including subject prerequisites and co-requisites, particularly\r\nduring admission or pre-enrollment. It also equips university staff and various college\r\ndepartments with tools to manage, track, and update curriculum structures in alignment\r\nwith updates from the Commission on Higher Education (CHED).\r\nDeveloped using the Evolutionary Prototyping Methodology, the system\r\nunderwent iterative design improvements based on user feedback, ensuring that\r\nfunctionality aligns with actual academic processes. A key feature includes the\r\nautomation of pre-enrollment course recommendations based on student grades,\r\nstreamlining academic advising and curriculum planning.	BSIS	Ma. Rema A. Lopera, Mary Queen M. Consumo, Riza Magbanua	["Curriculum viewing platform","Subject prerequisite tracking","Co-requisite management","Curriculum structure updating","Pre-enrollment course recommendation automation"]
62	ISAT U TRANSPORTATION MANAGEMENT SYSTEM	Managing vehicle schedules at Iloilo Science and Technology University is no longer a waste of faculty members' time. This research introduces the ISAT U Transportation Management System, an online application designed to provide secure scheduling and managing the vehicles of Iloilo Science and Technology University. Built with PHP, MySQL, JavaScript, and CSS, it offers an intuitive interface and robust backend, supporting various user roles like customers, staff, and administrator with tailored access. ISAT U Transportation Management System can only be used by a few users, the powerhouse will serve as the admin. They will take care of the vehicles and manage the schedules, and only the faculty, personnel and JO's will be able to schedule the vehicles. The system's usability and User Acceptance Testing (UAT) were evaluated using the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM). Data were collected through system testing to Powerhouse Personnel, JO's, and Faculty. Results showed a strong link between system usability and user satisfaction, with user attitude significantly influencing their intention to	BSIS	Joshua Rei M.Oresco, Jaypee T. Lindres, Rowen D. Labutap	["User role management","Vehicle scheduling module","Admin vehicle management","Online application interface","Backend database integration"]
